<Project slug="cyber-risk-register">
  <p class="lead">
    A gap analysis tells you what's missing. It doesn't tell you what could
    actually hurt the organisation. The risk register is the engine that
    translates gaps into prioritised, funded action.
  </p>

  <h2>The problem I wanted to solve</h2>
  <p>
    With 18 partially implemented controls, which one matters most? The risk
    register is the artefact most candidates either skip entirely or produce as a
    vague worry list. I wanted to build one with the methodological rigour that
    would survive an interviewer's deepest probe — "walk me through how you
    assessed this specific risk."
  </p>

  <h2>How I approached it</h2>

  <h3>Methodology before any risk</h3>
  <p>
    Before identifying a single risk I built the risk assessment methodology
    document. This is required by <span class="cite">ISO 27001 §6.1.2</span> and
    <span class="cite">ISO 27005</span>, but more importantly it's what auditors
    and interviewers test hardest. Without a documented methodology, every risk
    score is just an opinion.
  </p>
  <p>
    I built a five-by-five likelihood–impact matrix — never three-by-three,
    because three-by-three is too coarse to differentiate risks and is rejected by
    FSI risk frameworks. The likelihood scale anchors qualitative descriptions to
    frequency benchmarks so different assessors arrive at the same score. The
    impact scale spans four dimensions: financial (SGD thresholds), operational
    (disruption duration), regulatory (MAS enforcement, PDPA fines) and
    reputational (media, churn). The risk appetite statement explicitly prohibits
    accepting Critical risks for a MAS-regulated entity.
  </p>

  <h3>Completeness through NIST CSF</h3>
  <p>
    I identified 16 cyber risks across all five NIST CSF functions — Identify,
    Protect, Detect, Respond and Recover. The function mapping ensures
    completeness: if I'd identified 15 Protect risks and zero Detect risks, I'd
    have missed an entire functional domain. When an interviewer asks "how did you
    ensure comprehensiveness?", the CSF distribution is the answer.
  </p>

  <h3>Four-part decomposition</h3>
  <p>
    For each risk I decomposed it into threat source, threat action, vulnerability
    and asset at risk. This is what separates a professional register from a
    brainstormed list of concerns. The vulnerability column references findings
    from my gap analysis directly so the artefacts cross-reference each other.
  </p>

  <h3>Inherent vs residual scoring</h3>
  <p>
    Scoring was formula-driven. I calculated both inherent risk (without controls)
    and residual risk (with existing controls). The gap between the two reveals
    how effective the current controls actually are.
  </p>
  <div class="callout">
    <span class="section-mark">A worked example</span>
    <p>
      <strong>CRR-002 (ransomware)</strong> has inherent score 20 and residual
      score 20. This tells me that the controls are barely moving the needle.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>CRR-001 (privileged access abuse)</strong> drops from inherent 20 to
      residual 12. The controls help but are insufficient to reduce the risks.
    </p>
    <p>
      That delta is the conversation I want to have with the management.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Heat map and treatment plan</h3>
  <p>
    The 5×5 heat map plots all 16 risks by residual score — the single most
    important visual in the artefact, because it communicates the entire risk
    posture in ten seconds. The treatment plan documents 15 specific actions, each
    with a single named owner (not a team), a target month (not a quarter), an SGD
    cost estimate and a measurable KPI. "Improve endpoint security" is not a
    treatment action. "Deploy CrowdStrike Falcon EDR on all 120 endpoints,
    integrate with Microsoft Sentinel SIEM, MTTD target under 15 minutes" is.
  </p>

  <h2>What I produced</h2>
  <p>
    A five-sheet Excel workbook with the risk methodology, full register of 16
    risks, dashboard with auto-calculated metrics and charts, a populated 5×5 heat
    map and a detailed treatment plan. Alongside it, a one-page executive summary
    in Word designed for board presentation — metric cards, top-five risks ranked
    by residual score, phased budget and a specific recommendation to management.
  </p>

  <h2>What this demonstrates</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>I can quantify risk consistently using a documented methodology.</li>
    <li>I understand inherent vs residual risk and what the gap says about control effectiveness.</li>
    <li>I can communicate risk to two audiences — the technical register and the board summary.</li>
    <li>I can walk through any of the 16 risks under interview probing in under three minutes.</li>
  </ul>
</Project>
